 Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Popham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Hampshire, so called from an unattested short form of Old English <i>popel</i> ‘pebble’ + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’.","History: The Popham Colony was the first organized attempt to establish an English colony on the shores of what is now known as New England, then called Northern Virginia. George Popham of Hunstworth, Somerset, England, helped establish the colony at the mouth of the Kennebec River in 1607. It lasted for little over a year until it was abandoned in 1608. Although George died that same year, he may have had descendants or relatives with him as there are Pophams in the US who trace their family roots to the colony."],"variants":[{"name":"Poplin","meanings":["English: at least in part, a variant of   Popham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Popham was born in 1245, in Popham, Hampshire, England as the son of Gilbert de Popham. He married Agnes Clarke in 1265, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1292, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1245–1292":"1245–1292","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1279–1316":"1279–1316","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England","England":"England","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1245–1292":"1245–1292","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1279–1316":"1279–1316","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England","England":"England","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1245–1292":"1245–1292","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1279–1316":"1279–1316","1228–Male":"1228–Décédé","1228":"1228","1316":"1316","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1260":"1260","1292":"